Triumph of right-wing populists in Austria, overall they come to 29 percent
A noticeable weakening of both parties in the previous grand coalition and a clear strengthening of the right-wing populist parties brought the early parliamentary elections in Austria on Sunday, according to the first preliminary results.
Particularly severe losses were suffered by the Austrian People ’ s Party, where the position of former chairman Wilhelm Molterer is seriously on the tilt.
In contrast, the election leader of the Alliance for the Future of Austria (BZÖ), the Governor of Carinthia Jörg Haider, is preparing for a triumphant return to federal politics.
According to the results so far, the Social Democracy (Social Democrats) remains the strongest force in the country with 29.8% of the votes, but it loses 5.5% of the votes compared to the last elections in 2006.
Even worse, the Left Party cut down, losing almost nine percent of the votes at 25.6 percent.
These are the worst results of these two major parties in the post-war history of Austria, and this is a truly catastrophic result, especially for the People's Party, which had called for the early elections.
At the beginning of July, when the Democrats had withdrawn from the coalition, the People ’ s Party had a clear lead over the Social Democrats.
But voters have probably punished the party for failing the government.
Already in the first reactions to the results there was speculation about a possible resignation of the party leader and former Vice-Chancellor Wilhelm Molterer.
Observers believe that this could already be the case on Monday at an extraordinary meeting of the party board.
Such a development would probably pave the way to the most likely way out of the electoral debacle, that is to say to a renewal of the grand coalition of the Democrats and the Democrats.
In view of the strengthening of both right-wing populist parties - the Freedom Party (FPÖ) temporarily received 18 percent, while the BZÖ received eleven percent of the votes - the Social Democrats expressed their fear that the year 1999 could be repeated when the People's Party had agreed with the populists (at that time the Freedom Party was still uniform, in 2005 it split away from the BZÖ) with regard to a common government, which had even caused sanctions from the European Union.
It is obvious that Jörg Haider, who has already stated that he is prepared to cooperate with each party, is counting on this development from a return to Vienna to Austrian federal politics.
The party of the Greens also took part in the parliament, but it suffered slight losses and slipped from third to fifth among the Austrian political parties.
No other party has probably mastered the four trial hurdles and therefore did not enter Parliament.
