A seabed, larger than the mainland
The adjacent states today vehemently notified their claim to the new maritime areas.
After a UN convention, they are exercising their rights, which they agreed on in 1982 in Montego Bay in Jamaica.
It is mainly the area of the so-called continental lull, which often reaches up to a few hundred kilometers far from the shore of a country into the sea.
According to the Convention, this country has an exclusive right to all sources of continental welfare.
"Simply put, as a continental shelf, the part of the seabed and its soles is considered a natural continuation of the continent below the sea surface.
It transcends the boundaries of the shoreline, often also the boundary of two hundred nautical miles of the so-called exclusive economic zone ", explains Mikulka.
The application submitted by the relevant country to the Commission for setting the external borders of the continental lull must be substantiated by an extensive scientific technical documentation based on many cost-intensive investigations and measurements.
It is the result of many years of preparatory work.
"One of our tasks is to provide the Commission with legal and technical technical assistance.
The Commission has so far negotiated five applications from Russia, Brazil, Australia, Ireland and New Zealand.
So far, only the last three countries have been successful, "Mikulka adds.
The success of Australia, which was the first country to expand its maritime areas, recently met with an international response.
But New Zealand is also a winner - the expansion of the seabed approved by the Commission last week is about 1.6 million square kilometres, about six times more than the size of the country itself.
Both countries have invested millions of dollars in the investigation.
The profit that will flow to them in the future from the exploitation of the sea floor will, as they promise, have an invaluable value.
Other countries will also gradually submit their applications.
They can do this for ten years from the moment they ratify the "Agreement of Montego Bay".
Where the continental shelf ends, the area of the ocean floor begins, which is called "common heritage of humanity" by the Convention.
No state has a special position here.
The right to promote this is granted by an international institution established by the Convention.
"The seabed, however, is not a gold-digging land," says Director Mikulka with some exaggeration, adding that "individual areas are legally defined and the system is contractually anchored."
Czechs in the Pacific Ocean
Part of the sea floor also belongs to the Czech Republic today.
