Turkey Expands the Diplomatic Horizon
Long before Turkey sought to join the European Union, European powers were interested in penetrating deep into Turkey ’ s hinterland.
On the eastern side of the Bosphorus, perhaps just 20 steps within Asia, stands one of the finest relics of this failed imperial endeavor.
The Hydarpasha train station was designed by the two German architects Otto Ritter and Helmut Conu in the Neo-Renaissance style.
This is at least what the guides tell you.
The building sits rittlings at the end of the platforms with a tower at every corner of the front and thus looks like any provincial German town hall.
The rock is dirty.
The whole building decays about
But once you are inside the curved ticket counter, there is no doubt about the grandeur of the project, the westernmost access of which was this.
The station was opened in August 1908 by a German consortium, the Anatolia Baghdad Society.
Germany, which was a hatcher in the imperialist game, had to face its ambitions to dominate the Middle East through a train link to Damascus, Baghdad, and beyond what is now Saudi Arabia.
But Germany ’ s imperialist plans paralyzed during the First World War.
His railroad rails were attacked by Lawrence of Arabia and his Arabs.
The relative isolation from its surrounding region, generated by the insurmountable limits of the cold war, has disappeared.
British forces came out of Egypt and urged the Turks and their German allies from Palestine and Syria
And there was also bad news for the Hyderpasha train station.
In 1917, a ammunition train flew into the air, destroying the elaborate roof.
Turkish sources say it was sabotage.
Since then, it has slowly decayed, largely overlooked by history.
Today, however, this railway line serves, at least symbolically, as a gateway to Anatolia and all to the east to highlight the expansion of the diplomatic horizon of Turkey.
The ruling Justice and Development Party, the AKP, has introduced a completely new foreign policy for the country.
The relative isolation from neighbouring regions, generated by the limits of the Cold War, has disappeared.
There is now a policy of rapprochement.
Remarkably, the Turkish Government has good relations with Israel and Syria, with the Palestinian factions Hamas and Fatah, with Iran and Iraq and, of course, with the European Union and the United States.
In order to assess the key figures of this new foreign policy, I climbed the night train to the Turkish capital Ankara to visit one of the leading foreign policy experts of the AKP, Turkish MP Suat Kiniklioglu.
The next morning, about ten and a half hours later, after a bumpy ride on tracks that produced the same step of the old world in the well-known documentary "The Night Mail", I arrived in the Turkish capital, which is regarded as a new city, for the new secular state plan to turn my back on the Ottoman past.
But the AKP, known for its Islamist roots, represents a paradigm shift in Turkish unity
This has caused some distrust in the West, especially in Washington.
A taxi took me to the AKP ’ s main office, a specially designed, ultra-modern stone and steel construction, in a developing suburb, surrounded by half-finished shopping centers and pubs where middle managers met in suits, both men and women, to complete the first business of the day.
Suat Kiniklioglu could be a middle-right politician from almost any other political party in Europe.
Suit, tie, I'm sure he even packed a Blackberry.
"The goal of the party's foreign policy is now to reintegrate Turkey with its immediate neighbouring countries.
The Cold War was an exception, "he tells me.
Turkey had been cut off from its hinterland.
Nowadays it must look to the east and west at the same time.
There would not be either the one or the other.
It would have to do both.
"But surely Turkey could eventually," I asked, "be forced to decide?"
"Turkey," he said, "did not want to have to face this decision."
He then emphasised a point that almost everyone I spoke to here almost routinely said: Turkey's relations, not only with the Middle East, but also with the Caucasus and around the Black Sea, are just as beneficial for Europe and the United States as they are for Turkey.
With Turkey on board, the message seems to be able, in a figurative sense, to drive Europe as a whole on just those railway tracks east towards Asia and the Middle East.
Back at Hydarpashas station, after another night, largely sleepless, I thought of these two German lords Mr. Ritter and Mr. Conu, who had watched building this building 100 years ago.
How surprised they would have been to learn that Europe ’ s ambitions in the Middle East could now, to a large extent, be in Turkey ’ s hands.
And when I was waiting at the dock for the ferry that was to bring me back over the Bosphorus, I remembered that Turkey was always called "the sick man of Europe" in those days.
At the time, at least, there seemed not much doubt about which continent should be entitled to this fascinating country.
