'Auto's Bee ', which avoids collisions
In order to advance the development of the technologies for accident prevention, Nissan was inspired this time by nature, more precisely by the bees.
The Japanese company has developed a robot whose flight goes back to the swarm behaviour of bees and avoids accidents.
This robot is a biomimetic car robot drive or BR23C and represents the first step in the technologies for accident prevention.
The engineers from the Nissan Motor Co. technical development center developed this small robot in cooperation with Research Center for Advanced Science and Technology of the renowned University of Tokyo (Japan).
According to Kazuhiro Doi, Head of Technology PR and R & D Brand Management, the BR23C represents an extension of the four-layer Nissan safety shield.
This robot is designed to ensure that the cars of this brand are able to avoid collisions.
During the flight, each bee builds its own oval flight space, which is very similar to the Nissan safety shield.
But the most important are the facet eyes of the bee, which can see over an angle of 300 degrees in all directions, which allows them to fly undisturbed in their personal airspace without interruption.
The technicians developed the Laser Range Finder (LRF) to reproduce the all-round perspective.
He notices obstacles that are up to two meters apart in front of the BR23C and are in a radius of 180 degrees, calculates the distance up to the object and sends a signal to a onboard microprocessor, which is translated directly into signal for avoiding the collision
'At the moment when obstacle is noticed, the small robot will imitate the bee flight and immediately change direction by turning its wheels by 90º or even larger angles to avoid the collision.
The biggest difference to any other system is that this evasive maneuver takes place absolutely instinctively.
If it were not so, the robot could not be able to react with sufficient speed to avoid obstacles, 'explains Toshiyuki Andoh, the director of the Laboratory for Mobility and the senior engineer of this project.
In contrast to a bee, the robot can not deviate upwards or downwards, but also not obscure; it can only move on two dimensions and in the direction that allows it to rotate its wheels and not in the infinite directions and infinite ways as the bees do.
For this reason, Nissan has used the rotation function in addition to acceleration and braking functions, so that the small robot avoids collisions.
'This device only takes a couple of seconds to process the information and act according to this information.
It does not require neither the information nor the intuitive logic of the manoeuvres made to save, so it can work continuously with only a couple of dozens of KB of storage space.
This sounds surprising, but it is not about the GBs and not even about the MBs of the storage space.
This is the first step in the development of technologies for the immediate prevention of collisions, a technology that Nissan prophesied to introduce in the next ten years in production cars.
The robot works with Lithium-Polymer -batteries that are lighter and last longer than a variety of Lithium-Ions -batteries.
Another possible application of this technology in the future could be the integration of the unit with a GPS navigation system by satellite in order to lead up to the target while driving, avoiding the obstacles along the way.
