A week after a provisional agreement was made public, the two banks declared that MUFG will buy 9.9% of Morgan Stanley ’ s common shares at a uniform price of $25.25, representing a total of $3 billion.
The price assumed is below 19% of the share price of 31 August.
MUFG will invest an additional $6 billion in the acquisition of convertible shares, which will secure a 10% profit and can be resold at a price of $31.25.
Morgan Stanley said that global business will be conducted on the basis of a uniform average price of $29, 28% above the current price value.
However, the Morgan Stanley premier share fell by 6.79% to 23.07 dollars against 17.00 GMT.
'This strategic link is an important opportunity to accelerate the transition from Morgan Stanley to the status of a holding bank ', said John Mack, Director General of the American Group.
Morgan Stanley adopted this status last week, allowing him to expand their business to new areas, but under the supervision of the Federal Reserve.
Their connection with MUFG also confirms that the current financial crisis forces Wall Street ’ s biggest names to adopt a much more cautious stance than before.
The modalities presented on Monday also show that the agreement has changed over the past few days: Last Monday, Morgan had simply declared that it would sell up to 20% of its shares to Japan for about $8.5 billion.
'A week ago, 'said Toshihide Mizuno, Managing Director of MUFG in Tokyo,' we thought that the stake would consist entirely of common shares.
But given the current economic and market situation, we wanted to reduce the risks and secure ourselves. '
Based on a balanced average price, MUFG will pay 7% below its price value for its Morgan Stanley Shares.
And business will proceed with a reduction in earnings by about 20% per share.
The agreement provides that MUFG will be able to convert half of its preferential shares into ordinary shares in one year if the latter are exchanged more than 50% above the sales value within a given period, i.e. approximately $47.
Morgan Stanley assures that the funds supplied by MUFG will enable him to take advantage of investment opportunities, strengthen their balance sheet and increase their sales.
However, a group spokesperson refused to provide more detailed information on the strategic plans of the two new allies.
After MUFG's investment, Morgan Stanley should be able to register a payability ratio of about 15%, one of the best in this sector.
Morgan said that he had 'significantly' lowered his balance sheet since the end of August.
The last few weeks were tough for the group, which had to watch their exchange price drop by half, while the price of the insurance against insolvency increased.
This price decreased on Monday, but remained at a high level, at about 12%.
Goldman Sachs, the only other 'survivor' of Wall Street's major investment banks following the bankruptcy of Bear Stearns and Lehman Brothers and the purchase of Merrill Lynch, announced last week that he had withdrawn some $15 billion from Berkshire Hathaway, Warren Buffett's group.
Rafael Correa this Monday in Quito.
Re-establish the republic around the socialism of the 21st century.
This is the joint project of Venezuelan Hugo Chávez, Bolivian Evo Morales and Equatorial Rafael Correa.
It was that third party who, following the example of his like-minded and friends, put to the election this Sunday the plan of a new constitution.
Mission accomplished, because according to the public results of 80% of the votes, 64% voted 'yes' in the referendum.
According to these results, 28% voted 'no', 7% of the ballot papers were invalid and 0.7% were left empty.
For the constitutional project to be adopted, more than half of the votes cast must be cast.
On Sunday, two polls conducted at the polling stations and a count of a non-governmental organisation announced a clear victory for 'yes' and predicted him to be 63% to 70%.
In the night from Sunday to Monday Rafael Correa had demanded the victory of his constitutional project.
The 'Constitution has triumphed overwhelmingly', he had insured in Guayaquil, the seat of the government 280 kilometers southwest of Quito, and congratulated the Equatorians.
Of course Rafael Correa was congratulated by Chávez and Morales, but also by his Chilean like-minded Michelle Bachelet.
The election, held in silence in accordance with the observation of the Organization of American States (OAS), referred to a text consisting of 444 points to secure the 'new socialism' for which the President is committed.
The Constitutional Project transfers state power to the economy by giving it the sole right to 'development planning' in a country that lives largely on the extraction of oil by foreign companies and foreign currencies that send emigrants to the country.
The project, promoted by the Correa elected in 2006, also admits to the head of state greater power, which will be able to exercise up to two successive mandates of four years each, and will have the opportunity to dissolve the National Assembly.
Correa already announced that he will make use of this power and seek a new mandate in February 2009.
The Constitution also safeguards the principle of free medical care and education, which the President has already begun to introduce in this country with 13.9 million inhabitants, where 50% of the population live below the poverty line.
In the end, it also proposes to ban the presence of foreign troops, which will put an end to the agreement between Quito and Washington on the use of a equatorial base as the base for American anti-drug operations.
The 19 hostages were released in Chad
An Egyptian command launched the attack on the kidnappers of the eleven tourists and their eight companions who had been captured ten days ago.
They are in Cairo.
The eleven European tourists and their eight Egyptian companions, who were held in the desert for eleven days, were brought back to the Egyptian capital this Monday afternoon healthy and intact.
In the morning they were liberated from an Egyptian command in Chad.
Apparently in good condition, the hostages arrived on board a special aircraft at around 3.30 p.m. at the military base al ‑ Maza, right next to Cairo International Airport.
They were brought directly, without being able to speak to the press, aboard a helicopter to the hospital of Maadi, a suburb of Cairo, to be examined there.
They all enjoy 'best health' and the kidnappers' no ransom was paid ', said the Egyptian Minister of Tourism Zoheir Garanna on the field.
After being captured on September 19 by an off-road vehicle Safari at the foot of Mount Ouanat in the border area of Egypt, Sudan and Libya, the group of hostages was repeatedly taken from one hiding place by 35 unknown kidnappers.
There are eleven tourists - five Italians, five Germans and one Romanian - and eight Egyptians: two guides, four chauffeurs, a border guard and the director of the agency Aegyptus, organizer of the Safari.
An Egyptian security officer explained that 30 members of the special units, on board two helicopters, launched the attack at night, just before dawn.
'Shots fell on both sides and half of the kidnappers were killed, the rest fled, 'said this person who wants to remain anonymous.
He said that a total of 150 members of the Egyptian special units had been sent to Sudan, where they received support from German and Italian commandos.
The head of Italian diplomats Franco Frattini reported on Belgrade, where he is, about the role played by secret agents and elements of the Italian special units.
'We must acknowledge that we have achieved this result thanks to the professionalism and performance of our men from the secret service and the special units', he explained without further details.
He also denied that a ransom had been paid.
On the eve of the day, the Sudanese army had claimed that a patrol had stopped a terrain vehicle in which the kidnappers were found, of which they killed six, including the leader from Chad, and two arrests.
The army declared that they were in contact with a rebel group from Darfour, the Libération du Soudan -Unité (SLA -U) movement, but this movement immediately denied.
Letters - The silent majority of culture
A debate on the financing of culture makes headlines and is central to the current election campaign.
That is all the better.
But an area of our cultural life remains forgotten.
Who will rise and denounce the miserable sums of money granted to the small museums, to the archives, to the archaeological excavations or to the national historical places which are dying of starvation?
Which politician will dare to remind the Federal Government that it neglects its monuments and its culturally important buildings?
That in Quebec, as in Canada, there are no proper laws that effectively protect our cultural heritage?
Did you know that the French government is providing 3.5 million euros only for the restoration of the Château de Chinon in the Loire Valley?
With our American neighbors, the Constitution of their country states that the protection of cultural heritage belongs to the culture of the American, and that this cultural heritage must be protected by all citizens, all Members and all government districts, by mutual vote.
In Quebec, in the Association of History Societies of Quebec, at least 40,000 volunteers gathered in 211 historical societies strive to deal intensively with history, to save the numerous private archives with a few penny, and to preserve the archaeological remains.
They are also often the watchdogs of our cultural heritage, who protest with the power of despair when supporters and decision makers release their bulldozers on our old stones and forgotten cemeteries.
When will there be a stage for history and cultural heritage?
Benelux Governments nationalize parts of Fortis Bank
With a partial nationalization, the Benelux authorities want to help the Belgian Fortis Bank, which was in turmoil as a result of the US financial crisis: the three states provide a total of EUR 11.2 billion to the bank and insurance institution, which also has subsidiaries in Hungary.
The Governments of Belgium, Luxembourg and the Netherlands discussed at the highest level on the weekend, together with the President of the European Central Bank and the Competition Authority of the European Commission.
In the eurozone, Fortis is the first victim of the international financial market crisis that has lasted for a year, so decisions that are now being taken in connection with the Bank could be a precedent.
In line with the decision taken on Sunday night, all three states buy the bank ’ s respective shares at about 49 percent.
The Bank will probably sell part of its investments, notably the insurance activities purchased by ABN Amro last year.
The shares of Fortis have started a steep descent last week, and serious crisis scenarios have already emerged in the second half of the week.
However, analysts agree that the bank, with its 85,000 employees, is far too large for bankruptcy.
The securities of the Institute fell by 12% on Friday to a 14 year low.
Since January, the value of the shares has fallen by more than two thirds.
Given the current stock prices, the market value of the group is EUR 14 billion, but this is unrealistic according to management.
According to the management, the USD 700 billion US rescue package and the resulting uncertainty in the markets are to blame for the decline of Fortis ’ shares.
On Monday, however, the courses increased slightly.
Filip Dierckx was appointed new Director General of the Bank on Friday.
The financial institution was also looking for a private buyer, but there was no interested person with a factual offer.
However, the Belgian Government was trying to reassure - no investor was to tremble for his money, it said.
There has been no panic among customers, the bank ’ s branches have not been stormed.
In Hungary, Fortis has independent branches, but it also calls leasing companies its own.
Fox in the chicken stable
Due to a person ’ s drug use, life and health insurance in America often refuse to sign a contract with a customer.
Data protection experts fear that the data market could become uncontrollable.
"There are data protection programs that link the use of drug data to the consent of the person concerned.
These should be in independent hands, otherwise we trust the fox the chickens "- quotes the Washington Post Richard Dick, developer of the program for tracking prescription data.
Insurance determines the fees and payout amounts in the event of damage depending on the health condition of the customer, and if the risk is too high, the insurance will not be taken out at all.
In the past, the customer was sent to a medical examination and the contract was concluded only in knowledge of the results of the examination.
Ten years ago Dick invented a far more favourable method: Based on the customer's identification number, he obtained the data of the last year and a half from the pharmacies, i.e., which preparations were purchased, and the program calculates which illness the customer suffers from and how his health is.
For example, if he regularly buys large quantities of cholesterol lowering drugs, it could be concluded that his blood fat level is untraceably high, which would automatically place him in a higher risk group.
There are several versions of the program in circulation - some even define a risk calculator, so insurance only needs to do the paperwork, but there are minor difficulties.
One of the disadvantages is that many drugs can be taken for various purposes, such as migraine and hot flushes, but also depression.
The latter is a high risk factor from the perspective of insurers, while the above does not.
For the query and processing of the data, own companies have formed, which, before they receive the data, ask the patient for his consent.
They now have to do so by law, although omissions have not yet been punished.
Some companies even process the results of laboratory examinations and combine them with data on drug use, providing an even more accurate picture of patients ’ health.
More and more companies have access to the data, and control of their use is becoming more difficult at the same time.
Although there is a separate data protection law for health data, its effect only extends to health service providers and insurance companies.
The draft law has already been submitted to Congress, according to which the authorities could also control the data processing companies.
Dick Richard sees that this is too little, so he wants to develop his programme further, so that the data can only be passed on with the consent of the person concerned.
Another question is, of course, that the person concerned can hardly prohibit access to his or her data, because otherwise the insurance companies will not conclude a contract with him or her.
And so the chickens are somehow left to the mercy of the fox.
Global Menu from Marseille
European Union and India double trade
After both the European Union and India are each other ’ s leading trading partners, this was the main topic among other global problems at the ninth summit.
Today, there is also the French summit of India, which mainly discusses cooperation in the nuclear energy sector.
While the European Union recognises that India is an emerging, democratic power that should be given more votes and a say on international concerns, the member states have not yet been able to agree whether to support the permanent membership of New Delhi in the UN Security Council, or not.
This issue was not discussed yesterday at yesterday's ninth Marseille Summit.
The French President and current EU Council President Nicolas Sarkozy, as well as Commission President José Manuel Barroso and Chief Diplomat Javier Solana received Indian Prime Minister Manmohan Singh. An agreement was reached to double trade over the next five years, i.e. to raise it to a good EUR 100 billion.
Given that the exchange of goods increased from 25 billion to 55 billion between 2000 and 2007, this objective is not even so ambitious.
In this sense, the 26 existing civil flight agreements with India have also been legally consolidated into an agreement, so that aviation will also be encouraged in future.
By 2009, India intends to sign the Free Trade Agreement with the Union.
Sarkozy promised to speed up the pact.
The aim is to strike a balance in the current unbalanced relationship between the EU and India: while the Union is India's number one partner, New Delhi ranks only nine among the EU's partners.
The summit was dedicated to global concerns.
Among them was the situation in Afghanistan and Pakistan, or terrorism, which both sides strongly condemned, as well as the convening of a UN conference.
The Doha Round should also be completed, with both sides to blame for failure.
The EU underlined its commitment to its energy and climate programme, which is to reduce pollutant emissions by at least 20% by 2020.
India also agreed, as was the proposal to reach a sort of global compromise at the next climate summit and to reduce greenhouse gas production by 50% by 2050.
The rise in food prices should also be combated, so both support the convening of an international conference on the subject of financial crisis.
The Indian head of government today visits the French capital, where he will sign an agreement on the peaceful use of nuclear energy at a bilateral meeting.
In Paris, however, orders for French companies worth EUR 20 billion are expected for the construction of nuclear reactors in India.
According to agency reports, the agreement is to be decided for 15 years.
Over 300 Italian publishers in Frankfurt
Strong presence of Italian publishers at the International Frankfurt Book Fair.
More than 300 Italian publishers will be present at the 60th Book Fair, the most important international event for the acquisition of rights.
The international Frankfurt Book Fair expects more than 7,000 exhibitors from 101 countries to attend the current event. They will be distributed over the 171,790 square meters of the fair and will present over 403,000 titles. Turkey will be the guest of honour for the event.
Maria Giro, Undersecretary of the Ministry of Cultural Heritage and Activities, will represent the Italian Government in the exhibition hall during the opening ceremony: Italy will be represented in the 264 sqm exhibition space "Punto Italia".
This will be followed by a press conference near the room structure in the exhibition hall 5.0 of the book fair: on this occasion, figures, trends and perspectives around publishing in Italy will be discussed.
According to the data, the importance of books by foreign writers decreases in the whole, but especially in the adult and youth sectors.
The small plane of billionaire Steve Fossett disappeared a year ago
The small plane by Steve Fossett, the billionaire who disappeared on September 3, 2007 on a flight over the Nevada desert, was found.
The items have been found on a plateau of 3000 m altitude, in the area of the Sierra Nevada Mammoth Lakes between the states of California and Nevada.
However, there were no human remains inside the aircraft.
The Sheriff of Madera County, John Anderson, completely quenched the last doubts during a press conference: "The plane has been localized to which a troop was sent. Now we have the certainty that it is the plane with which Steve Fossett flew on the day of his disappearance."
Mr. Anderson also confirmed that no human remains were found in the aircraft or its vicinity.
The 63 year-old billionaire was declared dead in February.
The American Office for Traffic Safety (Ntsb) noted that a team was sent out a few hours after the aircraft was inspected, identifying the aircraft: it was the Bellanca 8kcab which was lost on September 3, 2007, after Fossett launched a 3-hour flight in Yerington, Nevada.
Yesterday, some of Fossett ’ s personal items were also found in California, near the Nevada border, by a couple near their home at the Mammoth Lakes.
These are two cards named Fossetts, both issued by the Federal Aviation Administration of illinois, cash and a jacket.
The search for Fossett had been abandoned one month after his disappearance.
The billionaire had conquered a place in history through a long sequence of records.
In 2002 he succeeded in the sixth attempt to circle the world ball in a hot-air balloon: a two-week, lonely flight.
Three years later he flew around the world in a single flight without a stopover by plane.
Among his many records is also a flight of 15445 m over the Andes, but this one with a co-pilot.
